result.execSummary:
The defendant Jack G Trebtoske was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting/Failing to Stop/Fleeing [Modifiers: Repeater], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(2t).
  • Operate w/o Valid License(2nd w/in3 Yrs) [Modifiers: Repeater], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 343.05(3)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

The defendant may not consume or possess alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns.

The defendant may not have any contact with Taylor Peterson or Jessica Bildeau.

The defendant must undergo an anger management assessment and psychological evaluation and follow thru with any recommendations or treatment plans.

The defendant must submit a DNA sample.
The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

Defendant Jack G Trebtoske in court with attorney Chad Lynch.  Defendant Jack G Trebtoske in custody.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 15CF176, 17CF11, 15CF74 and 17CF25. Called 3:18 PM. State - here for sentencing after revocation on 15CF74 and 15CF176. On other two cases - they were imposed and stayed (6 months each - consecutive to each other - 17CF11 and 17CF25) and have already been imposed. Lynch agrees. On 15CF176 - counts #1 and #2 and on 15CF74 - count #1. All parties have reviewed the revocation summaries, Lynch has no corrections or errors. State - 15CF176 - those counts are as repeaters as well. Court and Lynch agree. State - on 15CF74 - credit for 399 days and on 15CF176 - credit for 396 days - if everything is run concurrent to each other. Discussion on credit. Court is willing to give the parties another sentencing date to give everybody more time to figure out the credit. State would agree with that. Court - can proceed to sentencing and can always set matter for a hearing to determine the credit. State makes final argument prior to his recommendation - recommends on 15CF74 - 1 year in FC jail - consecutive to any and all sentences currently imposed, on 15CF176 - 9 months in FC jail - consecutive to 15CF74. Lynch makes final argument prior to his recommendation - recommends 1 year in FC jail on each case - concurrent to each other and concurrent to any sentence that he is currently serving. Trebtoske makes statement, asks Court to consider the argument of his counsel and also asks for concurrent time a well. Court sentences the defendant to the following: on 15CF74 - 1 year in FC jail - consecutive to any sentence that he is currently serving or are I&S; on 15CF176 - 9 months on each count - concurrent to each other but consecutive to 15CF74 and to any sentences that he is currently serving or are I&S, huber and good time allowed - eligible for community service under 973.03(3), 60 days after release from custody to pay any unpaid court costs/CO, right to appeal, set for a hearing to determine credit, adjourned.
